{"patient_id": "210", "personal_information": {"name": "", "gender": "Male", "dob": "1979-11-10", "age": 46}, "vitals": {}, "lab_results": [], "radiology_reports": [{"cpt_id": "1000000000070488", "cpt_name": "C.T. Chest High Resolution  (HR Chest)", "technique": "Multiple axial sections were taken through chest without I.V contrast injection (HRCT protocol).", "result": "Air trapping in bilateral lung fields. Pulmonary parenchymal distortion with multiple irregular areas of collapse consolidation, showing air bronchogram formation in the apical segment of right upper lobe with evidence of cylindrical / varicose bronchiectasis resulting in mild loss of volume. Focal bronchiectasis noted in the lingular segment of left upper lobe. No infiltration or consolidation noted in the left lung field. Normal trachea and major airway. Mild right sided apical pleural thickening. No pleural effusion seen on either side. 

Images of mediastinal window show a few calcified subcarinal lymphnodes. No definite mediastinal mass. A few sections through upper abdomen shows mildly enlarged liver measuring 16.8 cm. Mild to moderate degenerative changes in the thoracic spine.", "conclusion": "Apical pleural thickening with parenchymal distortion in the right upper lobe with multiple irregular foci of collapse consolidation showing air bronchogram formation, calcification and cylindrical bronchiectasis in the right upper lobe.  Features are in keeping with h/o pulmonary tuberculosis predominantly older changes however the possibility of active inflammatory process cannot be excluded. Clinical and lab correlation suggested for further evaluation. Comparison with the previous imaging, if available, would also be helpful. 

