{"patient_id": "212", "personal_information": {"name": "", "gender": "Female", "dob": "1960-03-03", "age": 66}, "vitals": {}, "lab_results": [], "radiology_reports": [{"cpt_id": "1000000000070488", "cpt_name": "C.T. Chest High Resolution  (HR Chest)", "technique": "Multiple axial sections were taken through chest without I.V contrast injection (HRCT protocol).", "result": "Increased antero posterior diameter of the thoracic cavity. Complete collapse of right middle lobe and anterior segment of right upper lobe and basal segments of right lower lobe secondary to bronchial stenosis Moderate right sided pleural effusion, only small lung parenchyma is visualized on right side. No definite area of consolidation or infiltration is noted in the left lung fields. No nodularity or bronchiectasis seen. Normal trachea. No pleural effusion seen on left side. 

Images of mediastinal window show multiple calcified densities likely enlarged calcified lymph nodes with possibility of superior vena cava obstruction. Dilated azygous and hemi-azygous system. Atherosclerotic calcification of aortic arch and coronary arteries. A few sections through upper abdomen are unremarkable. Varies also noted in anterior thoracic wall. Visualized skeleton shows severe degenerative changes with partial collapse of L1 vertebral body.", "conclusion": "Complete collapse of right middle lobe and anterior segment of right upper lobe and basal segments of right lower lobe secondary to bronchial stenosis. Moderate right sided pleural effusion. Calcified densities likely enlarged calcified lymphnodes with possibility of superior vena cava obstruction cannot be excluded. This needs further correlation with post contrast CT of the chest. Finding most likely suggest chronic inflammatory changes, including pulmonary tuberculosis. 

